════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2ead4); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b98229; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#191817; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">Quiet, elevated and family-focused: the outer north's large-block suburb.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Ferny Hills sits between Keperra and Ferny Grove on Brisbane's outer northern corridor, offering something genuinely scarce within the city limits: large residential blocks on elevated, hilly terrain with tree-lined streets and a quiet, established character. The suburb's position on the Ferny Grove train line corridor, with both the Keperra and Ferny Grove stations accessible, gives residents a real commute option without the inner-ring price point. For families who have weighed space against location and decided the outer-ring equation works, Ferny Hills is where many of them land.
    </p>
